Let the fare for the first kilometer be \( x \) and the fare for each successive kilometer be \( y \).

From the given data:
\[
\begin{cases}
x + 19y = 37.70 \quad \text{(for 20 km)} \\
x + 25y = 48.50 \quad \text{(for 26 km)}
\end{cases}
\]

Subtracting the first equation from the second gives \( 6y = 10.80 \), so \( y = 1.80 \). Substituting back yields \( x = 7.90 \).

The fares are \(\boxed{\{7.90, 1.80\}}\).
